          <h2>About the Program</h2>
          <p>Our Core Civics & Advocacy Training program is designed specifically for returning citizens—individuals with firsthand experience in the criminal legal system who are now home and ready to use their voices to create change.</p>
          
          <p>We believe that those closest to the problem are closest to the solution. This program transforms lived experience into advocacy expertise, creating a powerful force for reform in Arizona.</p>
          
          <h2>Training Curriculum</h2>
          <h3>Civics & Government 101</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Arizona state government structure and processes</li>
            <li>How a bill becomes a law in Arizona</li>
            <li>Understanding legislative sessions and committees</li>
            <li>Local government and criminal justice decision-making</li>
            <li>Voting rights restoration and civic participation</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Advocacy Skills</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Effective storytelling for policy change</li>
            <li>Testifying at legislative hearings</li>
            <li>Meeting with elected officials</li>
            <li>Coalition building and partnership development</li>
            <li>Media engagement and public speaking</li>
            <li>Social media advocacy strategies</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Policy Analysis</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Reading and understanding legislation</li>
            <li>Researching criminal justice data</li>
            <li>Identifying harmful vs. helpful policies</li>
            <li>Developing policy recommendations</li>
            <li>Amendment drafting basics</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h2>Program Components</h2>
          <h3>12-Week Intensive Training</h3>
          <p>Our flagship program includes:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Weekly 3-hour sessions (in-person and virtual options)</li>
            <li>Guest speakers including policymakers and advocates</li>
            <li>Hands-on practice with real legislation</li>
            <li>Cohort model for peer support and networking</li>
            <li>Resource binder and digital toolkit</li>
            <li>Certificate of completion</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Advanced Advocacy Fellowship</h3>
          <p>For graduates ready to take the next step:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>6-month paid fellowship opportunity</li>
            <li>Direct involvement in legislative campaigns</li>
            <li>Mentorship from experienced policy directors</li>
            <li>Coalition representative role</li>
            <li>Speaking engagement opportunities</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h3>Alumni Network</h3>
          <p>Ongoing support and connection through:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Monthly alumni meetings</li>
            <li>Continuing education workshops</li>
            <li>Advocacy opportunity alerts</li>
            <li>Peer mentorship program</li>
            <li>Leadership development track</li>
          </ul>
          
          <h2>Who Can Participate</h2>
          <p>This program is specifically designed for:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Returning citizens with lived experience</li>
            <li>Family members of incarcerated individuals</li>
            <li>Community advocates from impacted communities</li>
            <li>Individuals committed to criminal justice reform</li>
          </ul>
          
          <p><strong>All participants must complete an application and interview process.</strong></p>
